<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-894-718  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 894 718.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DG Review  Oct 1989 v10 n4 p28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Who needs state of the art? (used equipment as an alternative tonew equipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fitch, Ron.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Used computer equipment can be a viable, cost-effectivealternative to state of the art equipment.andP;  While used equipmentis less expensive to purchase, it can be more difficult andexpensive to service than new equipment, and can be physicallylarger and have greater power requirements as well.andP;  Beforepurchasing used equipment, its performance specifications andsoftware or hardware limitations should be ascertained, and theprice and availability of warranties and service should bedetermined.andP;  Used equipment may require extra programming effort,but this should be offset by its inexpensive purchase price.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Used EquipmentEquipment AcquisitionGuidelinesCost.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>